{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516802","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516802"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:46:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:46:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12717"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12717","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12717"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.2,0.04,0.49,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5172"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78073"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5172","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5172"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12717"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63495"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2770"},{"type":"tags","id":"2840"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8759"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8849"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26735"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43348"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78073","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78073"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 48-year-old woman presents with a six-month history of joint pain in both her hands. She experiences joint stiffness after she wakes up in the morning. This stiffness improves with activity. Over the same period, she has noticed weight loss, malaise and redness with dryness of her eyes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination of her hand joints there is no deformity, but she has tenderness and swelling of MCP and PIP joints of both hands, with restrictive and painful movement of her fingers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations show a haemoglobin of 108g/L (120-150), WCC of 9.9 x 10^9/L (4 - 11), ESR 38 mm/hour (\u0026lt;\u003Csub\u003E \u003C/sub\u003E20 mm/hour) and CRP 19 mg/L (\u0026lt;5 mg/L). Anti-CCP and Rheumatoid factor (RF) are positive. ANA is negative.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following features is most characteristic of this disease?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Episcleritis","Heberden\u2019s nodes","Livedo reticularis","Nodules at extensor surface","Onycholysis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe presentation and investigations are suggestive of rheumatoid arthritis. From all the above given features \u003Cstrong\u003Enodules at extensor surface \u003C/strong\u003Eare characteristic of rheumatoid arthritis. These are firm, painless swellings that occur at pressure points or over bony prominences, such as the elbows, fingers, or feet. Rheumatoid arthritis is a chronic systemic autoimmune inflammatory disease characterised by a symmetric polyarthritis that most commonly affects the small joints of the hands and feet, sparing the distal interphalangeal joints. Extra-articular involvement of organs such as the skin, heart, lungs, kidneys, salivary glands and eyes may be present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHeberden\u2019s nodes\u003C/strong\u003E are hard bony swellings that develop in the distal interphalangeal joints. They are a sign of osteoarthritis and are caused by formation of osteophytes of the articular cartilage in response to repeated trauma at the joint. Rheumatoid arthritis spares the distal interphalangeal joints.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELivedo reticularis \u003C/strong\u003Eis a common skin finding consisting of a mottled reticulated vascular pattern that appears as a lace-like purplish discoloration of the skin.\u003Ca href=\u0022https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Livedo_reticularis#cite_note-Bolognia-1\u0022\u003E\u003Csup\u003E \u003C/sup\u003E\u003C/a\u003EThe discoloration is caused by reduction in blood flow through the arterioles that supply the cutaneous capillaries, resulting in deoxygenated blood showing as blue discoloration. It is associated with connective tissue disorders such as systemic lupus erythematosis, and antiphospholipid syndrome but is not present in rheumatoid arthritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOnycholysis\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by the painless detachment of the nail from the nail bed, usually starting at the tip or sides. It can be caused by trauma to nail, fungal infections of the nail, exposure to chemicals such as detergents, chemotherapy drugs and tetracyclines, some systemic diseases such as psoriasis, thyroid disease, and autoimmune disorders like lupus or pemphigus but is not known to be associated with rheumatoid arthritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpiscleritis \u003C/strong\u003Eis not characteristic of RA, though it can occur in association with RA but its occurrence is more common with other autoimmune diseases like Sjogren\u0027s syndrome etc., therefore it cannot be regarded as the characteristic feature for rheumatoid arthritis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Painless nodules at extensor surfaces are found in rheumatoid arthritis.","Rheumatoid arthritis is characterised by symmetric polyarthritis, often affecting the small joints of the hands and feet.","Positive anti-CCP and rheumatoid factor are indicative of rheumatoid arthritis."],"references":["Deane KD, Holers VM. Rheumatoid Arthritis Pathogenesis, Prediction, and Prevention: An Emerging Paradigm Shift. Arthritis Rheumatol. 2021 Feb;73(2):181-193. doi: 10.1002/art.41417. Epub 2020 Dec 8. PMID: 32602263; PMCID: PMC7772259. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32602263/","Tilstra JS, Lienesch DW. Rheumatoid Nodules. Dermatol Clin. 2015 Jul;33(3):361-71. doi: 10.1016/j.det.2015.03.004. PMID: 26143419. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26143419/","Evangelisto A, Werth V, Schumacher HR. What is that nodule? A diagnostic approach to evaluating subcutaneous and cutaneous nodules. J Clin Rheumatol. 2006 Oct;12(5):230-40. doi: 10.1097/01.rhu.0000240034.72958.2f. PMID: 17023809. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17023809/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63495"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12717"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63495","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63495"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-09T12:52:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-09T12:53:55+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5172"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78073"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"descript